definition.value: A member of the class of triazoles that is 1H-1,2,4-triazole substituted by an aminocarbonyl group at position 3. It is the major catabolite and aglycon of ribavirin.
An azacycloalkane that is cyclohexane in which one of the carbons is replaced by a nitrogen. It is a metabolite of cadaverine, a polyamine found in the human intestine.
An optically active form of glutamine having L-configuration.
A tertiary ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of chlorprothixene resulting from the protonation of the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.

'Lipids' is a loosely defined term for substances of biological origin that are soluble in nonpolar solvents. They consist of saponifiable lipids, such as glycerides (fats and oils) and phospholipids, as well as nonsaponifiable lipids, principally steroids.

A nucleoside analogue that is N(4)-hydroxycytidine in which the 5'-hydroxy group is replaced by a (2-methylpropanoyl)oxy group. It is the prodrug of the active antiviral ribonucleoside analog N(4)-hydroxycytidine (EIDD-1931), has activity against a number of RNA viruses including SARS-CoV-2, MERS-CoV, and seasonal and pandemic influenza viruses. It is currently in phase III trials for the treatment of patients with COVID-19.
A nucleoside analogue that is cytidine which carries a hydroxy group at the N(4)-positon. It has broad-spectrum antiviral activity against influenza, SARS-CoV , SARS-CoV-2 and MERS-CoV.
A member of the class of phylloquinones that consists of 1,4-naphthoquinone having methyl and phytyl groups at positions 2 and 3 respectively. The parent of the class of phylloquinones.
Any polysaccharide containing a substantial proportion of aminomonosaccharide residues.
The R-enantiomer of nicardipine.

A dihydropyridine that is 1,4-dihydropyridine substituted by a methyl, {2-[benzyl(methyl)amino]ethoxy}carbonyl, 3-nitrophenyl, methoxycarbonyl and methyl groups at positions 2, 3, 4, 5 and 6, respectively.
An organosulfate oxoanion that is the hexanion of suramin resulting from the deprotonation of the six sulfo groups; major species at pH 7.3.
An alcohol that consists of cyclohexane bearing a single hydroxy substituent. The parent of the class of cyclohexanols.
Any six-carbon monosaccharide which in its linear form contains either an aldehyde group at position 1 (aldohexose) or a ketone group at position 2 (ketohexose).
A  benzenediol comprising of a benzene core carrying two hydroxy substituents ortho to each other.
An alpha-tocopherol that has R,R,R configuration. The naturally occurring stereoisomer of alpha-tocopherol, it is found particularly in sunflower and olive oils.
A biomacromolecule consisting of large numbers of monosaccharide residues linked glycosidically. This term is commonly used only for those containing more than ten monosaccharide residues.
An alpha-amino acid that is phenylalanine bearing a hydroxy substituent at position 4 on the phenyl ring.
A penicillin in which the substituent at position 6 of the penam ring is a phenylacetamido group.
The parent compound of the citrulline class consisting of ornithine having a carbamoyl group at the N(5)-position.
A solution of ammonia in water.
An aldopentose, found in the embryos of most edible plants and used in medicine to test for malabsorption by administration in water to the patient.
An alpha-amino acid that is glutaric acid bearing a single amino substituent at position 2.
Catechol in which the hydrogen at position 4 is substituted by a 2-aminoethyl group.
A beta-D-glucan in which the glucose units are connected by (1->4) linkages.
An iron group element atom that has atomic number 26.
Any nucleoside where the sugar component is D-ribose.
An alpha-amino acid that is pentanoic acid bearing two amino substituents at positions 2 and 5.

An iodothyronine compound having iodo substituents at the 3-, 3'- and 5-positions. Although some is produced in the thyroid, most of the 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine in the body is generated by mono-deiodination of L-thyroxine in the peripheral tissues. Its metabolic activity is about 3 to 5 times that of L-thyroxine. The sodium salt is used in the treatment of hypothyroidism.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of dodecanoic acid (lauric acid); major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha-D-glucan in which the glucose units are connected by (1->6) linkages.
That part of DNA or RNA that may be involved in pairing.
A 5-methoxyfurocoumarin that is psoralen substituted by a methoxy group at position 5.
A member of the class of imidazoles that is 1H-imidazole substituted at position C-4 by a 2-aminoethyl group.
A butenedioic acid in which the double bond has cis- (Z)-configuration.
A class of aminophospholipids in which a phosphatidyl group is esterified to the hydroxy group of serine.
A monosaccharide derivative that is  hydroquinone attached to a beta-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 4 via a glycosidic linkage.
A alpha,beta-unsaturated monocarboxylic acid that is ethene substituted by a carboxy group.
An acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbon having the general formula CnH2n+2, and therefore consisting entirely of hydrogen atoms and saturated carbon atoms.
